Documentation for the program "cohfit"
-------------------------------------

COMMAND NAME:   cohfit

SYNOPSIS:  Calculates baseline-based coherence times

SYNTAX:  cohfit [-c cotime] [-d device] [-e examfile ] [-f fitmask ] [-l] \
            [-g RxC] [-m msglevel] [-o outfile] [-s loss] [-x] averagedAlist

OPTION FLAGS:   -c cotime
                        Sets an upper limit to the coherence time that
                        can be generated by cohfit.  This is needed for
                        cases where little coherence loss exists, very
                        long times can be formally fitted, and later
                        programs can get confused.  Defaults to 392 sec.

                -d device
                        Specifies the output graphics device for the plots
                        of amplitude and SNR versus segmentation time.
                        The specification is in the standard PGPLOT form
                        of filename/devicetype (e.g. test.ps/ps).  You may
                        append /pdf to the device name to convert to pdf
                        (e.g. test.ps/vcps/pdf).

                -e examfile
                        Specifies a base filename pattern to be used to
                        generate additional outputs; it should include %d
                        or %<digits>d for the baseline-pol file index. If
                        that is missing -%d.data will be appended.  Using
                        this unique .data, .gnu, .sum and .pdf files will
                        be generated (provided you have gnuplot(1) in your
                        PATH at configuration time).  The .data files are
                        generated on per baseline-pol basis, the others
                        appear on a per scan boundary basis.

                -f fitmask
                        A mask of bits specifying what amplitude and SNR
                        fits are to be attempted:
                            0x01 = standard plateau-slope (loss) for amp
                            0x02 = plateau-only (no-loss) for amp
                            0x04 = slope-only (all-loss) for amp
                            0x10 = a three-point parabolic fit at SNR max
                            0x20 = cubic spline fit of SNR curve (GSLv2.8)
                            0x40 = cubic spline fit of SNR curve (GSLv2.7)
                        The default is 0x77 (all of them).  The argument
                        must begin with 0x or 0X.  Assuming no issues in
                        the fit process, the best reduced chisq for amp.
                        and the cubic spline fit on SNR will be used.

                -l
                        Provide plot labels.  (More detailed commentary
                        is available with the -e option output, so these
                        are off by default.)

                -m msglevel
                        Verbosity control parameter, ranging from -3 to +3,
                        with lower numbers being more verbose.  The default
                        value is 2 with more detail on fits at level 1.

                -o outfile
                        If specified, this flag directs the A-file output
                        of cohfit to the named file.  If omitted, cohfit
                        writes its output to stdout.

                -s loss
                        The default is 5% loss (0.05); you can change
                        this to some other value with this option.
                -x
                        Shorthand for "-d /xw", the xwindow display.

                -g RxC
                        Specify the number of Rows x Columns in the plot.
                        The default is 2x2 which is good for 4 pol products.
                        Alternatively, when -e is used this may be a filename
                        allowing adjustment of gnuplot options, see below.

ARGUMENTS:      averagedAlist
                        One or more input A-files which contain data generated
                        by "average -c".  These data have been segmented at a
                        variety of segmentation times by "fringex", then
                        incoherently scan averaged using "average".

ENVIRONMENT:    None.


DESCRIPTION:

The program cohfit is designed to automate the process of determining the 
coherence times of data for many baselines and scans.  The input to the program
is a family of A-file lines for each baseline and each scan.  The family of
lines consists of scan-length incoherent averages for a variety of segmentation
times.  Depending on the coherence properties of the original data, the
amplitudes should show a plateau at short segmentation times, followed by
increasing coherence loss and decreased amplitude as the segmentation time
increases.  The SNR should show a maximum somewhere near the point at which
the amplitude plateau (signifying negligible coherence losses) ends.  Cofit
constructs these functions of amplitude and SNR and fits simple functional
forms to them.  It then uses these fits to determine the segmentation time
at which no more than 5 percent amplitude loss occurs, and at which the SNR
is maximized for weak sources (these two segmentation times are generally
not equal).  The coherence times thus determined are written into the 
appropriate fields in the A-file line, and one line is written out per
baseline/scan.  This information is then used by subsequent HOPS software.

The plateau-only and slope-only fits for amplitude are provided in the event
that the data is not well fit by the plateau/coherence loss expected model.
The GSL spline framework was changed after version 2.7; the GSL 2.8 version
supports both; there should be no difference between the two, but if both are
available in the underlying GSL installation, both are available.

The program will accept only data written by "average -c".  In many cases, the
script cohfit_driver.sh will serve to run cofit after the appropriate fringex
and average commands.  Note that cohfit will refuse to fit anything if you
have less than 4 segments.

When -e is used before the -g parameter, it may refer to a file with RxC
and a number of other tweaks to the gnuplot defaults.  If the file does
not exist a template file with explanations is output which may be edited
and used.  The RxC values may be specified in this file and used in the
PGPLOT version of output.
